253,http://www.armslist.com/posts/2807253,For Sale:  Remington No.8 In .32 Remington Caliber,"South East Virginnia, Virginia, United States",$ 500,"Listed On: Tuesday, September 22, 2015",Rifles,Remington                                                                                ,no type,Semi-automatic                                                                                ,Rifle,"NOTE: it is the buyers responsibility to confirm that this firearm is legal to own in your state and/or locality.

****LOWER PRICE **** Offered for your consideration is one (1) . Using the Remington Society serial number dating information, this No. 8, serial number 23262, was manufactured in 1911, and returned to Remington for repair in November of 1934, (return code of RC3) stamped on the head of the barrel shroud.

The Remington No.8 was originally introduced as the Remington Auto Loading Rifle in 1906. It was designed by John Moses Browning, uses the same long-stroke recoil operating system as his newly designed shotgun, the A5. It has a 22‚Äù jacketed barrel and a five-round fixed box magazine, and was produced in the following calibers: 25 Remington, 30 Remington, 32 Remington. Four additional chamberings for the Model 8 were added later in this order of introduction. They were: 35 Remington; 30 Remington,(also referred to as the 30-30 Remington), 32 Remington and finally the 25 Remington (referred to as the 25-35 Remington).
The No.8 Remington was the first mass-produced semi-automatic rifle chambered for a round more powerful than the most popular deer cartridge of the day, the .30-30 Win.
Many hunters continue to use the Remington No.8 rifles in the field today, 108 years after the original patent was issued to John M. Browning.

Mainly because these rifles have stood the test of time for 108 years of use in the field, at times under horrible conditions, these rifles continue to hold a special place in the hearts of many hunters, authors, and artists. Adventures using them are still remembered in often told tales around a campfire in a deer camp, in the written material of well known authors, and in many forms of artwork, both old and new.

Below is the information on the Dies and Conversion kit from Dillon.  This includes a Dillon .40S&W Case Gage in the cost.
Sizing/Depriming Die

Our sizing/depriming dies feature a unique ""floating decap assembly"" with a snap spring that throws the spent primer off the pin and eliminates the problem of primer ""draw back"" that often occurs when decapping military brass. The primary feature of Dillon's size die design the long, tapered carbide ring with a radiused opening remains unchanged.

That radiused opening, and its importance to progressive reloading, is one of the reasons why our seat and crimp dies are better. We found a way of manufacturing these dies that has enabled us to make the lead-in radius even bigger! The bigger radius makes progressive loading with our equipment even smoother but that's still only a part of the story.
Bullet Seating Die

Our new quick-disassembly seat die allows the user to disassemble and clean the seat die without losing adjustment. In this manner, bullet lube and shavings can be quickly removed from the die, thereby guaranteeing a constant seating depth. We've incorporated a ""flip-flop"" seating stem and a clip that enables you to remove the die insert and change the seating stem from round nose to semi-wadcutter without unscrewing a seating stem out of the die body. We've always included both types of seating stems, but the new double-ended design makes it a simple matter to remove a pin, reverse the seating stem, make any minor seating depth adjustments that may be necessary and go on loading in a fraction of the time it used to take.
Crimp Die

We've made it easy for you to remove the die insert for cleaning without having to change the critical crimp adjustment. Once your crimp die is set for the proper amount of crimp, you'll never have to change it. This is especially good news for all of you who load lead bullets! Before, you had to unscrew the die from the toolhead and disassemble the die in order to remove any bullet lube or lead residue. Then, you had to start from square one to re-adjust the crimp. Those days are over. All you have to do now is pop a clip and the die insert drops into your hand for cleaning.
NOTE: All Dillon Pistol Die sets include our sizer/ decap die, seat die and a separate crimp die. (Taper crimp for autos; accu-crimp for revolvers.)
Conversion Kit
Contains: Shellplate, powder funnel, and locator buttons. available in all calibers"

659,http://www.armslist.com/posts/2807659,For Sale:  Remington No.8 In .30 Remington Caliber,"South East Virginnia, Virginia, United States",$ 500,"Listed On: Saturday, August 15, 2015",Rifles,Remington                                                                                ,no type,Semi-automatic                                                                                ,Rifle,"NOTE: it is the buyers responsibility to confirm that this firearm is legal to own in your state and/or locality.

****LOWER PRICE**** Offered for your consideration is one (1) Remington No.8 in .30 Remington caliber. Using the Remington Society serial number dating information, this No. 8, serial number 61735, was manufactured in 1930, and returned to Remington for repair in February of 1942, (return code of LL3) stamped on the head of the barrel shroud.
The receiver has been drilled and tapped for a side mount scope mount. Also a Williams peep sight has been mounted to the rear of the receiver.

The Remington No.8 was originally introduced as the Remington Auto Loading Rifle in 1906. It was designed by John Moses Browning, uses the same long-stroke recoil operating system as his newly designed shotgun, the A5. It has a 22‚Äù jacketed barrel and a five-round fixed box magazine, and was produced in the following calibers: 25 Remington, 30 Remington, 32 Remington. Four additional chamberings for the Model 8 were added later in this order of introduction. They were: 35 Remington; 30 Remington,(also referred to as the 30-30 Remington), 32 Remington and finally the 25 Remington (referred to as the 25-35 Remington).
The No.8 Remington was the first mass-produced semi-automatic rifle chambered for a round more powerful than the most popular deer cartridge of the day, the .30-30 Win.
Many hunters continue to use the Remington No.8 rifles in the field today, 108 years after the original patent was issued to John M. Browning.

Mainly because these rifles have stood the test of time for 108 years of use in the field, at times under horrible conditions, these rifles continue to hold a special place in the hearts of many hunters, authors, and artists. Adventures using them are still remembered in often told tales around a campfire in a deer camp, in the written material of well known authors, and in many forms of artwork, both old and new.
